So what is POOLER SESSION MODE?
The REAL problem (no tech words)

Think of a restaurant 🍽️

Restaurant has 100 chairs

That’s it. No more.

Now:

500 people come

If everyone sits → chairs break → chaos

👉 Database = restaurant
👉 DB connections = chairs

PostgreSQL says:

“I can only handle ~100 people at a time.”

What happens without a pooler? 💥

Your app is dumb and greedy:

Every user comes

App says: “Here, take a new chair 🪑”

101st user comes → CRASH

Result:

App down

Errors

Panic

“Why production broken??”

Enter: Connection Pooler (the bouncer 😎)

Now imagine a bouncer at the door.

He says:

“Only 100 people inside”

“When someone leaves, next one comes”

That bouncer = connection pooler

What the pooler does (simple)

Keeps only 100 DB connections open

Reuses them

Stops your app from opening unlimited ones

So instead of:

500 users = 500 DB connections ❌


You get:

500 users = 100 DB connections ✅


DB stays alive. Everyone happy.

Now where does SESSION MODE fit in?

Session mode decides HOW people sit.

SESSION MODE = “One person, one chair, don’t move”

Rule:

User comes in

Gets a chair

Sits there until they leave

Nobody else can use that chair

Example:

User A → Chair #1 → keeps it
User B → Chair #2 → keeps it
User C → waits outside 😬

What does this help with? (REAL help)

Because the user:

stays on same chair

nothing changes under them

their stuff stays safe

Meaning:

DB remembers them

No mix-ups

No half work

Good when:

Doing serious work

Multiple steps

Money, admin, reports

Why not always use session mode?

Because it’s slow & greedy.

If:

100 users sit

101st user comes

👉 He waits.
Even if chairs are idle.

That’s why:

App feels slow

Users complain

DB not dead, but app is choking

One-line super simple summary

Connection pooler stops the database from dying.
Session mode decides that one user keeps one connection till they’re done.

Final brutal truth

Session mode:

✅ Safe

❌ Not scalable

It solves:

correctness

stability

It sacrifices:

speed

concurrency
